<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Secretary of State Meets PRC Leaders </TI></H3>
<H4>   Shattuck-Wei Meeting `Interference' </H4>
<F P=102> HK1203075094 Hong Kong AFP in English 0726 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK1203075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 12 (AFP)--US Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher's visit to Beijing got off to a stormy start 
Saturday as China slammed a senior U.S. official for holding an 
illegal meeting two weeks ago with the country's leading 
dissident. "The action constituted interference in China's 
internal affairs in disregard of the Chinese law," Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen said in a clear reference to the meeting 
between Assistant Secretary of State for Human Rights John 
Shattuck and celebrated dissident Wei Jingsheng in Beijing on 
February 27. 
  China was "deeply disappointed" by the incident, Foreign 
Ministry spokesman Wu Jianmin quoted Qian as telling Christopher 
during talks here which Shattuck himself attended. 

</TEXT>

